{{Politics of Grenada}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in [[Grenada]] on 6 November 2018.<ref name=CNS>[https://caribbeannewsservice.com/now/antigua-antigua-and-grenada-to-hold-ccj-referendum-in-november/ ANTIGUA – Antigua and Grenada to hold CCJ Referendum in November] Caribbean News Services, 2 July 2018</ref> The proposed constitutional amendment, which voters ultimately rejected, would have made the [[Caribbean Court of Justice]] (CCJ) the final [[Appellate court|court of appeal]], replacing the British [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]], and renamed the Supreme Court.<ref name=NG1>[http://www.nowgrenada.com/2018/07/is-grenadas-ccj-referendum-really-about-access-to-justice-part-2/ Is Grenada's CCJ referendum really about access to justice? Part 2] Now Grenada, 5 July 2018</ref> A slightly different proposal was previously made in a [[Grenadian constitutional referendum, 2016|2016 referendum]], but was also rejected by voters.<ref>[http://jamaica-gleaner.com/article/news/20180423/grenada-hold-another-ccj-referendum Grenada To Hold Another CCJ Referendum] The Gleaner, 23 April 2018</ref>
[[Antigua and Barbuda]] also held [[Antiguan constitutional referendum, 2018|a referendum]] on joining the CCJ on the same day; that vote also failed to pass.<ref name=CNS/><ref>{{cite news |title=Antiguans and Barbudans reject efforts to adopt CCJ |url=https://caribbeannewsservice.com/now/antiguans-and-barbudans-reject-efforts-to-adopt-the-ccj-as-final-court/ |accessdate=7 November 2018 |publisher=Caribbean News Service |date=6 November 2018}}</ref>
==Question== Voters were asked to respond YES or NO to the following question: :''Do you approve the Bill for an Act proposing to alter the constitution of Grenada cited as Constitution of Grenada (Caribbean Court of Justice and renaming of Supreme Court) (Amendment) Bill 2018?''<ref>{{cite news |title=PM tells voters not to be swayed by misleading information about the referendum |url=http://www.nowgrenada.com/2018/11/pm-tells-voters-not-to-be-swayed-by-misleading-information-about-the-referendum/ |accessdate=6 November 2018 |publisher=Now Grenada |date=5 November 2018}}</ref>
==Results== No votes outstripped yeses by 12,133 to 9,846, on a turnout of 28%. [[Prime Minister of Grenada|Prime Minister]] [[Keith Mitchell]], whose government had called the vote, said he was "disappointed" but that he was "in total acceptance of the results".<ref>{{cite news |title=Grenada: Prime Minister Mitchell disappointed at results |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/grenada-prime-minister-mitchell-disappointed-at-results/ |accessdate=7 November 2018 |publisher=St. Lucia News Online |date=6 November 2018}}</ref>
