{{Orphan|date=December 2017}}
{{Merge to|Meo (telecommunication service)|date=August 2018}}
[[File:+ Smart Net - advertisement offering service packages.png|thumb|right|500px|Portuguese [[Internet service provider]] [[MEO (Portugal)|MEO]] offers to sell additional access to particular data services in this October 2017 advertisement. Many media sources republished this ad as a starting point for discussions about net neutrality.]]

The '''MEO advertisement for data access''' is an advertisement by Portuguese telecommunications provider [[MEO (Portugal)|MEO]] in which the company offers to sell additional access to particular online services beyond a user's general data allotment. The advertisement was the focus of a discussion beginning in October 2017 and covering topics including [[net neutrality]], [[Internet in Portugal]], [[European Union law]], the United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], and a range of social issues.

==History==
MEO posted their advertisement for Internet services on their own website. On 26 October 2017, [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] [[United States Representative|U.S. Representative]] [[Ro Khanna]] posted a screenshot of MEO's website to his [[Twitter]] feed while stating that their sales model was a violation of net neutrality and bad.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Khanna|first1=Ro|authorlink=Ro Khanna|title=In Portugal, with no net neutrality, internet providers are starting to split the net into packages|url=https://twitter.com/rokhanna/status/923701871092441088?lang=en|website=@rokhanna|publisher=[[Twitter]]|language=en|date=26 October 2017}}</ref>

Following Khanna's message, the technology community at [[Reddit]] discussed it on 27 October.<ref>{{cite web|author=/r/technology commentators |title=In Portugal, with no net neutrality, internet providers are starting to split the net into packages. This is the future of the Internet if the FCC gets its way. It's not theory. It's happening already.|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/technology/comments/79770i/in_portugal_with_no_net_neutrality_internet/|website=[[Reddit]]|language=en|date=27 October 2017}}</ref> Net neutrality advocate [[Cory Doctorow]] featured the ad as an illustration of a net neutrality violation on ''[[Boing Boing]]'' on 28 October.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Doctorow|first1=Cory|authorlink=Cory Doctorow|title=Portuguese non-neutral ISP shows us what our Trumpian internet will look like |url=https://boingboing.net/2017/10/28/warning-taken-as-suggestion.html|website=[[Boing Boing]]|language=en|date=28 October 2017}}</ref> ''[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]'' reported that the ad showed a net neutrality violation on 30 October.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Coren|first1=Michael J.|title=Without net neutrality in Portugal, mobile internet is bundled like a cable package|url=https://qz.com/1114690/why-is-net-neutrality-important-look-to-portugal-and-spain-to-understand/|website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|date=30 October 2017}}</ref> [[Tim Wu]], the legal scholar who defined the term "net neutrality", commented on 30 October after reading the Quartz article that the ad did show a violation of net neutrality.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wu|first1=Tim|authorlink1=Tim Wu|title=Web has been disappointing lately, I'll admit, but look what it looks like without Net Neutrality (in Portugal)|url=https://twitter.com/superwuster/status/925181150506692608|website=@superwuster|publisher=Twitter|language=en|date=30 October 2017}}</ref> From this point the discussion was far ranging. By 22 November MEO published a response to the attention.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Machado|first1=Manuel Pestana|title=O que é a Internet neutra? Portugal apontado como mau exemplo nos Estados Unidos|url=http://observador.pt/2017/11/22/o-que-e-a-internet-neutra-portugal-apontado-como-mau-exemplo-nos-estados-unidos/|website=[[:pt:Observador (jornal)|Observador]]|language=pt-PT|date=22 November 2017}}</ref>

==Responses==
Many media sources reported that the sales model which the image described was a bad thing for being a violation of net neutrality.<ref>
